COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 356, L.D. 537
1 (2) Information about the minor's relationship to a close relation; or
2 (3) Any item of information concerning the minor specified in paragraph A.
3 §9102. Doxing of minor prohibited
4 A person may not engage in conduct that constitutes doxing of a minor. A person that
5 violates this section may be subject to a civil action for damages pursuant to section 9103.
6 §9103. Civil action for damages
7 A minor may bring a civil action against a person who violates section 9102 for
8 injunctive relief, actual damages, compensatory damages, any combination of those
9 remedies or any other appropriate relief.
10 1. Attorney's fees and costs. A plaintiff who prevails in a civil action under this
11 section is entitled to an award of attorney's fees and costs.
12 2. Punitive damages. A plaintiff who proves by clear and convincing evidence that
13 the doxing of a minor was committed with malice or motivated by the race, color, religion,
14 ethnicity, national origin, citizenship status, sex, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity
15 or expression, physical or mental health condition or disability of the minor or of a close
16 relation of the minor is entitled to an award of punitive damages in addition to any other
17 remedy.
18 3. Defenses. It is a defense to a civil action brought pursuant to this section that a
19 person disclosed personal identifying information of a minor for the sole purpose of:
20 A. Reporting conduct that was reasonably believed to be unlawful or to constitute a
21 crime to a law enforcement officer or law enforcement agency;
22 B. Publishing, disseminating or reporting conduct by a public official, law
23 enforcement officer or law enforcement agency that was reasonably believed to be
24 unlawful, to constitute a crime or to constitute an abuse of authority; or
25 C. Engaging in lawful activity protected by the United States Constitution or the
26 Constitution of Maine pertaining to speech, assembly, press or petition, including to
27 address a matter of public concern.
28 4. Minors as parties. A minor may be a party to an action under this chapter only
29 when the minor has a representative through whom the action is brought or defended
30 pursuant to the Maine Rules of Civil Procedure, Rule 17(b).'
31 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
32 number to read consecutively.
33 SUMMARY
3344 This amendment, which is the majority report of the committee, makes the following
3355 changes to the bill.
36 1. It clarifies that a person engages in doxing of a minor if the person intentionally,
37 knowingly or recklessly discloses personal identifying information of the minor and
38 consciously disregards a substantial risk that the disclosure will cause, and in fact the
39 disclosure either directly or indirectly causes, certain types of harm to the minor or a close
40 relation of the minor, including stalking, physical harm, serious damage to the minor's or a
Page 3 - 132LR0650(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 356, L.D. 537
411 close relation's property or that the minor or a close relation of the minor reasonably fears
422 for the minor's physical safety or the physical safety of a close relation.
3 2. It provides that a minor may obtain a protection from harassment order against a
4 person who doxes the minor.
5 3. It expands the definition of "personal identifying information" of a minor, including
6 by adding information about the minor's citizenship status or passport number.
7 4. It amends the definition of "personal identifying information" to provide that
8 disclosing a photograph of a minor that was taken in a public place or that has previously
9 been made publicly available does not constitute the disclosure of personal identifying
10 information unless the photograph is accompanied by the minor's name, information
11 identifying the minor's close relations or other personal identifying information of the
12 minor.
13 5. It clarifies that a minor may be a plaintiff or a defendant in a civil action involving
14 doxing of a minor only if the minor is represented as required by the Maine Rules of Civil
15 Procedure, Rule 17(b).
16 6. It clarifies that compensatory damages awarded in a civil action against a person
17 who doxes a minor may include past and future medical expenses, lost earnings, pain,
18 suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress and loss of enjoyment of life.
19 7. It strikes the provision of the bill authorizing an award of treble damages and instead
20 provides that a plaintiff who demonstrates by clear and convincing evidence that the doxing
21 of a minor was motivated by the race, color, religion, ethnicity, national origin, citizenship
22 status, sex, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity or expression, physical or mental
23 health condition or disability of the minor or of a close relation is entitled to an award of
24 punitive damages.
25 8. It clarifies that a person is not liable in a civil action for doxing of the minor if the
26 person's conduct was protected either by the United States Constitution or by the
27 Constitution of Maine.
